<full-text-retrieval-response xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/svapi/article/dtd" xmlns:bk="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/bk/dtd" xmlns:cals="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" xmlns:ce="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" xmlns:ja="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/ja/dtd" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:sa="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/struct-aff/dtd" xmlns:sb="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/struct-bib/dtd" xmlns:tb="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/table/dtd" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:xocs="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/xocs/dtd" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:dcterms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:prism="http://prismstandard.org/namespaces/basic/2.0/" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"><coredata><prism:url>https://api.elsevier.com/content/article/pii/S0301479723027639</prism:url><dc:identifier>doi:10.1016/j.jenvman.2023.119975</dc:identifier><eid>1-s2.0-S0301479723027639</eid><prism:doi>10.1016/j.jenvman.2023.119975</prism:doi><pii>S0301-4797(23)02763-9</pii><dc:title>Evaluating the costs of primary forest conservation in the Democratic Republic of Congo, implications for policy and practice </dc:title><prism:publicationName>Journal of Environmental Management</prism:publicationName><prism:aggregationType>Journal</prism:aggregationType><pubType>fla</pubType><prism:issn>03014797</prism:issn><prism:volume>352</prism:volume><prism:startingPage>119975</prism:startingPage><prism:pageRange>119975</prism:pageRange><articleNumber>119975</articleNumber><dc:format>text/xml</dc:format><prism:coverDate>2024-02-14</prism:coverDate><prism:coverDisplayDate>14 February 2024</prism:coverDisplayDate><prism:copyright>© 2023 Published by Elsevier Ltd.</prism:copyright><prism:publisher>Published by Elsevier Ltd.</prism:publisher><dc:creator>Bush, Glenn</dc:creator><dc:creator>Taye, Fitalew Agimass</dc:creator><dc:creator>Fleming, Christopher</dc:creator><dc:creator>Samndong, Raymond Achu</dc:creator><dc:description>
                  Accurate cost information is needed to assess the trade-offs in land management choices for policy and markets to effectively scale forest conservation impact. Choice of valuation method can affect value estimates of the costs associated with forest conservation for heterogenous rural households in poorly functioning markets. We present empirical evidence on the divergence in measures between a market price and contingent valuation estimate for costs of local forest access restrictions from household surveys deploying quantitative valuation methods, conducted in two forest communities in the Democratic Republic of Congo. Household demographic characteristics and attitudes of the household on forest use significantly influence required levels of compensation to participate in forest protection. Quantitative knowledge of such costs can help in the design of efficient and effective policies to protect primary forests aimed at reducing the drivers of deforestation.
               </dc:description><openaccess>0</openaccess><openaccessArticle>false</openaccessArticle><openaccessType/><openArchiveArticle>false</openArchiveArticle><openaccessSponsorName/><openaccessSponsorType/><openaccessUserLicense/><dcterms:subject>Natural climate solutions</dcterms:subject><dcterms:subject>Economic values</dcterms:subject><dcterms:subject>Biodiversity</dcterms:subject><dcterms:subject>Conservation</dcterms:subject><dcterms:subject>Primary forests</dcterms:subject><dcterms:subject>Payments for ecosystem services</dcterms:subject><dcterms:subject>Carbon markets</dcterms:subject><link href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/article/pii/S0301479723027639" rel="self"/><link href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301479723027639" rel="scidir"/></coredata><objects><object ref="gr2" category="standard" type="IMAGE-DOWNSAMPLED" multimediatype="JPEG image file" mimetype="image/jpeg" width="386" height="283" size="91068">https://api.elsevier.com/content/object/eid/1-s2.0-S0301479723027639-gr2.jpg?httpAccept=%2A%2F%2A</object><object ref="gr1" category="standard" type="IMAGE-DOWNSAMPLED" multimediatype="JPEG image file" mimetype="image/jpeg" width="811" height="294" size="109443">https://api.elsevier.com/content/object/eid/1-s2.0-S0301479723027639-gr1.jpg?httpAccept=%2A%2F%2A</object><object ref="gr2" category="thumbnail" type="IMAGE-THUMBNAIL" multimediatype="GIF image file" mimetype="image/gif" width="219" height="161" size="74343">https://api.elsevier.com/content/object/eid/1-s2.0-S0301479723027639-gr2.sml?httpAccept=%2A%2F%2A</object><object ref="gr1" category="thumbnail" type="IMAGE-THUMBNAIL" multimediatype="GIF image file" mimetype="image/gif" width="219" height="79" size="70166">https://api.elsevier.com/content/object/eid/1-s2.0-S0301479723027639-gr1.sml?httpAccept=%2A%2F%2A</object><object ref="gr2" category="high" type="IMAGE-HIGH-RES" multimediatype="JPEG image file" mimetype="image/jpeg" width="1712" height="1255" size="20520