            <ce:date-received day="25" month="8" year="2023"/>
            <ce:date-revised day="21" month="12" year="2023"/>
            <ce:date-accepted day="26" month="12" year="2023"/>
            <ce:miscellaneous id="misc0010">Handling Editor: Lixiao Zhang</ce:miscellaneous>
            <ce:abstract xml:lang="en" id="abs0010" view="all" class="author"><ce:abstract-sec id="abssec0010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="abspara0010" view="all">Accurate cost information is needed to assess the trade-offs in land management choices for policy and markets to effectively scale forest conservation impact. Choice of valuation method can affect value estimates of the costs associated with forest conservation for heterogenous rural households in poorly functioning markets. We present empirical evidence on the divergence in measures between a market price and contingent valuation estimate for costs of local forest access restrictions from household surveys deploying quantitative valuation methods, conducted in two forest communities in the Democratic Republic of Congo. Household demographic characteristics and attitudes of the household on forest use significantly influence required levels of compensation to participate in forest protection. Quantitative knowledge of such costs can help in the design of efficient and effective policies to protect primary forests aimed at reducing the drivers of deforestation.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            
            <ce:keywords xml:lang="en" id="kwrds0010" view="all" class="keyword">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0020">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0010">
                  <ce:text>Natural climate solutions</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0015">
                  <ce:text>Economic values</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0020">
                  <ce:text>Biodiversity</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0025">
                  <ce:text>Conservation</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0030">
                  <ce:text>Primary forests</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0035">
                  <ce:text>Payments for ecosystem services</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="kwrd0040">
                  <ce:text>Carbon markets</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da0010" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0025">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Data will be made available on request.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec1" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0030">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Natural climate solutions (NCS) are a range of land management approaches that promise to reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions whilst maintaining or enhancing economic productivity in a landscape (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib25" id="crosref0040">Griscom et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>), a key mechanism on the supply side of the emerging global carbon market. NCS pathways are associated with many technologies long established in the policy literature for the protetction and enhancement of landscape environmental benefits e.g. forest and biodiversity conservation or watershed management, or for agricultural productivity e.g. improving soil organic matter conservation and nutrient retention.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Protection is critical (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib9" id="crosref0045">Cook Patton et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>).; the largest 1% of old growth trees contain almost 50% of the world's forest carbon. Moreover, older forests have the capacity for continuous carbon sequestration (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib28" id="crosref0050">Harris et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Each year forests remove about 30% of global anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib32" id="crosref0055">Lutz et al, 2018</ce:cross-ref>). Mature forests, particularly those that are naturally evolved and little disturbed by industrial activity, have inherent biodiversity and ecosystem intactness, making them more resilient against fire, drought, and invasive species (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib34" id="crosref0060">Mackey et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). This is particularly significant as old growth landscapes across temperate, tropical, and boreal forests come under increasing threat from expanding agriculture and forestry operations. The economic and social drivers of deforesttaoin globally are dievrse and context specific (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib2" id="crosref0065">Andoh et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). Understanding the local econom social tradeoffs in land use decisoins will be critical in desinging pragamatric, scalable programs to provide the right incentives for local landscape actors to engage in forest protection, managment and restoration.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">Whilst reducing fossil fuel emissions remains the highest priority, from a global carbon management perspective, NCS are a critical opportunity to limit global warming, offering around 30% of the cost effective potential to mitigate global emission by 2030 (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib53" id="crosref0070">WEF, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). However there appears to be a popular misconception that conserving forests as an NCS approach is, or should be a “cheap” abatement alternative. The origin of this misplaced dogma lies in some influential work on marginal abatement cost curves (MACC) for alternative emissions reduction tehcnologies (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0075">Enkvist et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref>), which severally underestimates the costs of forest conservation (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib17" id="crosref0080">Eakins et al., 2011</ce:cross-ref>). Necessarily <ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0085">Enkvist et al. (2010)</ce:cross-ref> rely on publicly available data on abatement costs. In the case of less developed economies, one significant source of error in estimating the opprtunity cost of forest conservation compared to alternative abatement tehcnologies, is the lack of accurate, publicly available data on the significant non-marketed benefits from forests. How much will it cost to conserve tropical forests is of primary concern in this study and methods to reveal those costs in light of significant non-marketed benefits? Whilst a growing literature is available on forest values in tropical nations, comparison of the estimates made using different vlaution techniques are few, even fewer, are studies assessing the socio-economic factors contributing to those differences.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">This study presents novel empirical data on the costs of reducing the local drivers of deforestation, examining both the financial and total economic costs of achieving primary forest conservation. We generate critical insights into PES design in the context of remote rural communities in central DRC, where there is a local trade-off between deforestation for agricultural production and forest conservation. In addition, we provide a direct comparison of the relative significance of sociodemographic variables on market price (direct use) and contingent valuation (CV) (total economic value) estimates of forest value, a novel contribution to the valuation literature.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">Specifically, we examine socioeconomic and demographic factors, measures of social capital, perceptions of and experiences in forest use, as well resource use conflict that might cause divergence between value measures. We are not aware of a published study that is able to evaluate the same suite of socio-economic factors to provide such insights. We also illustrate the strengths and weaknesses of the different forest valuation approaches, as well as the role of governance and socio-economic parameters in determining a household's propensity to use forest resources. In so doing, we fill a known research gap by providing DRC-specific value estimates. As noted by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib47" id="crosref0090">Taye et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref> in their meta-analysis of the economic value of ecosystem services provided by the world's forests, the tropical forests of the DRC, relative to their importance in providing carbon storage and biodiversity conservation, are poorly represented in the extant valuation literature.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">Globally, 18% of the world's tropical forests lie outside of areas formally protected by state regulation, rather, they are on privately held or public land under common property and customary tenure arrangements (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0095">FAO &amp; UNEP, 2020</ce:cross-ref>). While the public good outcomes of forest conservation provide a case for government involvement, the existence of diverse and complex private property rights regimes creates difficulties in designing and enforcing regulatory mechanisms. Difficulties with imposing restrictions that generate private opportunity costs have led policymakers to consider voluntary approaches to improving environmental outcomes, including the use of market mechanisms to encourage private landholders to produce public good environmental outcomes (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib27" id="crosref0100">Hanley et al., 2012</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib45" id="crosref0105">Schilizzi and Latacz-Lohmann, 2013</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">The <ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0110">Dasgupta Review (2021)</ce:cross-ref> highlights that payments for ecosystem services (PES) schemes, are becoming a familiar tool for conserving and restoring ecosystems and the services they provide (p. 203). The review concludes that:<ce:displayed-quote id="disp0010">
                        <ce:simple-para id="dspara0010" view="all">
                           <ce:italic>… offering incentives to farmers to adopt practices that support biodiversity and ecosystem services – for example through agri-environment schemes and payments for ecosystems services (PES) – should be further developed.…the effectiveness of PES schemes has proved to be mixed in low-income countries, but even there such schemes hold great potential. And wherever they are adopted, their success depends on their design and scale of funding</ce:italic>. (p.490)</ce:simple-para>
                     </ce:displayed-quote>
                  </ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">The scale of funding needed is of primary concern for this study. Specifically, in the context of the biodiversity rich, yet threatened, forests of the central Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), this study examines the financial and economic costs of achieving primary forest conservation via a PES approach through evolving carbon market mechanisms i.e. the generation and sale of carbon credits from forest landscapes. Two dominant financial mechanisms to provide the capital to scale forest landscape protection, management, and restoration; are the national compliance market, reducing emissions from deforestation and forest degradation and the enhancement of carbon stocks (REDD+) and carbon offsetting through the voluntary carbon market. Primary forests such as those found in central Africa are a conservation priority. They support high concentrations of biological diversity, sequester and store substantial amounts of carbon, and play a vital role in hydrological cycles among providing a variety of other ecosystem services (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib33" id="crosref0115">Mackey et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). For many in tropical less developed economies, primary forests are also critically important for cultural and spiritual reasons; and are a significant contributor to the livelihoods of the Indigenous Peoples and local communities around the world who call these forests home (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib31" id="crosref0120">Kormos et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">The DRC forest estate and associated land store vast amounts of carbon and help regulate one of the world's largest river basins. The DRC is also a unique reservoir of biodiversity: it ranks fifth in the world for plant and animal diversity. Its natural habitats range from mangroves to glaciers and volcanoes. It contains more Natural World Heritage Sites than the rest of Africa combined. These forests are of high global importance in terms of avoided deforestation for carbon and biodiversity conservation through PES schemes. DRC's forest-based environmental services are increasingly of global interest, having a high potential for traditional economic development through resource exploitation but, importantly, are the focus of much national and international effort under climate change frameworks through the national program for REDD+ and for global voluntary carbon offset markets.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">Since it was first proposed in 2005, REDD + has been a promising results based payments approach to help secure the world's primary forest estates. REDD+ is essentially a global market mechanism, developing a voluntary incentives framework for economic agents to tackle deforestation. Through “payments for performance” contracts, also termed results-based payments, countries, sub-national jurisdictions, communities and individuals can be rewarded for forest conservation actions to reduce their own emissions and offset others. Schemes such as REDD + have been growing in popularity as a mechanism for translating external, non-market values of ecosystem services into price (direct cash payment) incentives for local actors to provide such services (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib19" id="crosref0125">Engel et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>) and have been highlighted as an innovative approach to achieving conservation and socioeconomic development goals (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib51" id="crosref0130">Vincent, 2010</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">Caution is warranted; as noted by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0135">Dasgupta (2021)</ce:cross-ref> in reference to PES schemes more generally, there are situations where REDD + could be bad for poverty reduction and distributive justice, and some rural poor may become worse off than they were previously; a concern that is relevant to the DRC (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0140">Samndong et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>). This raises the critical issue of equity in PES design (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0145">Dunlop and Corbera, 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib48" id="crosref0150">Tegegne et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) and of the need to understand how affected communities and households view proposals to access and distribute REDD + finance, as well as how policy performance and results should be assessed, and the extent to which co-benefits are generated and shared. Supporting shifts in power and gendered relations may – at first glance – come at the expense of short-term efficiency, nevertheless such shifts are necessary if REDD+ is to meet its goal of emission reductions effectively and equitably (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib52" id="crosref0155">Wong et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>). This is a critical observation, as it reflects on the true marginal abatement costs of conserving tropical forest carbon more generally and the misconception that it is a low-cost strategy to both mitigate global greenhouse gas emissions and promote biodiversity conservation (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib46" id="crosref0160">Seymour and Busch, 2016</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">In a functional market economy, PES mechanisms (direct cash payments) work as a positive incentive when the benefits derived from increased provision of ecosystem services exceed the cost of provision, in theory making both ecosystem service beneficiaries and providers better off (win-win). However, PES in developing countries, where markets do not function well, is proving to be more difficult to implement, owing to the complex organizational and institutional conditions in these contexts (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib38" id="crosref0165">Muradian et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib54" id="crosref0170">Wunder, 2013</ce:cross-ref>). Despite considerable promise and interest in the use of PES schemes worldwide and increasing assessments of the benefits and costs of such schemes, there is little documentation of actual or potential changes in program participants’ welfare (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0175">de Sherbinin et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0180">Groom and Palmer, 2008</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib29" id="crosref0185">Jack et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">Two key challenges exist for policy makers in assessing the economic costs and benefits in deciding if a PES scheme can work; first, what level of benefit will result in a desired behavioral change (opportunity cost estimation) and second, regarding equitable sharing of benefits, how social and economic factors affect welfare values. The corresponding question in emerging voluntary markets for avoided deforestation credits could be formulated on the supply side as “how much is my forest carbon worth?” or on the demand side “how much should I pay for a given carbon credit? Quantifying the variable social and financial values related to forests and their contribution to local livelihoods is important in accounting for the variable economic welfare benefits derived from forest values amongst heterogeneous forest using households. Better knowledge of the target population values and attitudes relevant to forest conservation objectives could contribute to deciding if PES schemes are an appropriate mechanism to achieve objectives, or in designing compensation or benefit sharing mechanisms, or subsequently in assessing if expected changes are likely to take place, and guide modification to improve adoption and durability. Fundamentally in a market based mechanism for carbon, if values are not aligned e.g. prices for carbon are not competitive with the local opportunity cost of alternatives, there will be no incentive for people in the landscape to participate and no possibility of scaling impact.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Assessing the relevance of PES schemes for achieving primary forest and biodiversity conservation is particularly relevant in the context of the DRC. Around 26 of the 154 million ha of forests are in protected areas (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib14" id="crosref0190">Doumenge et al., 2015</ce:cross-ref>). This means over 80% of primary forests are at risk from rapidly growing small holder “slash and burn” agriculture. The DRC's national program to reduce carbon emissions from deforestation and forest degradation is focused on avoided deforestation strategies through a mix of regulatory and voluntary mechanisms (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0195">Government of the Democratic Republic of Congo, 2012</ce:cross-ref>). This in part involves developing an incentive framework to promote forest conservation above alternative land uses amongst heterogeneous private agents. Forest loss is the leading source of DRC greenhouse gas emissions and a key driver of declining biodiversity (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib24" id="crosref0200">Government of the Democratic Republic of Congo, 2018</ce:cross-ref>). The DRC government aims to move towards a performance-based system of payments to achieve avoided deforestation based on verifiable emission reductions. Of key importance in terms of focusing policy and practice significance is that almost 98% of national forest loss is driven by smallholder subsistence agriculture (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib35" id="crosref0205">Molinario et al., 2020</ce:cross-ref>). However, the possibilities for smallholder farm households to adjust their behavior in order to optimize the use of their resources in response to novel policy objectives, in a context of imperfect markets, are sharply limited by their asset positions and by the contexts where they operate (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib11" id="crosref0210">de Janvry and Sadoulet, 2006</ce:cross-ref>). Their limited access to productive assets and the unfavorable contexts where they operate result in high levels of risk aversion and credit market failures. A deeper knowledge of the social and economic values derived from forests to quantify the drivers of forest loss are critical for identifying actions to promote effective, efficient, and equitable strategies to achieve avoided deforestation targets.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">It is often assumed that the costs of policies and programs can be measured using market prices, or when markets are distorted, it is possible to adjust the observed market prices to reflect the true economic value of a good or service. However, this is not possible in all cases of market failure. Nonmarket valuation techniques such as contingent valuation allow us to value goods and services when the appropriate market is absent. i.e., goods and services that are not traded on markets or cannot be traded on markets resulting in no observed market price. This is typically in the case of forest products that are harvested and consumed within the home by rural people (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib3" id="crosref0215">Angelsen et al., 2014</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib7" id="crosref0220">Campbell and Luckert, 2002</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">To address the two key challenges for policy makers identified earlier, quantifying the variable social and financial values related to forests and their contribution to local livelihoods is important in accounting for the variable economic welfare benefits derived from forest values amongst heterogeneous forest using households. Better knowledge of the target population values and attitudes relevant to forest conservation objectives could contribute in the first instance to deciding if PES schemes are an appropriate mechanism to achieve objectives, in designing compensation or benefit sharing mechanisms, and subsequently in assessing if expected changes actually take place, allowing for modification to improve adoption and durability.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">Skepticism regarding the ability of analysts to provide reliable measure of the economic impact of forest use restrictions are driven by general misunderstanding amongst many policy managers regarding the significance of different value measures. Between financial (market prices) and economic (non-market valuation), the former is limited in scope to the subset of community losses normally measurable through some market transaction or equivalent (for goods consumed within the household), whereas the economic method tries, in addition, to capture wider cultural values (attachment to the land; spiritual values) and other intangibles such as greater food security (e.g. the ability to rely on forest foods when crops fail). A quantitative economic approach based on the measurement of both priced and un-priced household losses is essential, to maximize the effectiveness of benefits sharing mechanisms to adequately packages to offset local opportunity costs and provide ongoing incentives for respecting newly adopted restrictions over forest use (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib56" id="crosref0456">Wunder and Wertz-Kanounnikoff, 2009</ce:cross-ref>). However, the suitability of local opportunity cost assessments has also come into question. At issue is the ability of economists to adequately assess the levels of compensation necessary under variable market and institutional conditions, (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib57" id="crosref0457">Gregersen et al., 2010</ce:cross-ref> ).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">This study follows an approach developed by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0225">Bush et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref>, who in a similar context of substance farming households in tropical forest landscapes in Uganda, investigated the difference between opportunity cost estimates of forest resources harvested in economic welfare terms versus financial terms. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0230">Bush et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref> demonstrated that the opportunity cost of forest conservation was almost as much as 50% of total annual household income and nearly 20 times more than the estimated financial cost value of forest goods. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0235">Bush et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref> discuss, but do not conclude, that the differences in value measures may reflect the level of household integration into markets; where the substitutability of goods for money in a peasant farming economy, in the face of acute scarcity, is low (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib18" id="crosref0240">Ellis, 1993</ce:cross-ref>). This hypothesis is tested in the present study. Using a wealth disaggregated approach, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib6" id="crosref0245">Bush et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref> concluded that social (non-market) values associated with forest income were greater for low-income households than for high-income households. This may reflect the difference between household dependence for low-income households (few alternatives to forest income) versus use as a livelihood alternative for high-income households. Again, this hypothesis is tested in the present study.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">The rest of this paper is organized as follows. Section <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10640-021-00601-w" id="intref0010" xlink:type="simple">2</ce:inter-ref> discusses data collection and methods of analysis. Section <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10640-021-00601-w" id="intref0015" xlink:type="simple">3</ce:inter-ref> presents and discusses results. Section <ce:cross-ref refid="sec4" id="crosref0250">4</ce:cross-ref> concludes.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec2" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0035">Data and method</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0040">Survey design and sampling</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">We employ a structured household interview to elicit socio-economic data on local forest values as part of a broader investigation into the proximate and underlying causes of deforestation. A detailed account of the sampling strategy and social and economic conditions of the respondent communities is available in <ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0255">Samndong et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref>. We summarise below to give immediate context for this article.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">Data were collected from 360 households in the towns of Bikoro and Gemena, according to a multi-stage stratified random sample, accounting for household heterogeneity in the dense humid forest region of Équateur Province, DRC. Beginning in 2013, Bikoro and Gemena territories were established as target areas for a REDD + capacity building program and community level pilots implemented by the Woodwell Climate Research Center (then operating as Woods Hole Research Center), in partnership with the DRC Ministry of Environment and Sustainable Development and supported by the Congo Basin Forest Fund. Noting that the province boundaries have since changed due to decentralization and administrative reorganization, the pre-decentralization Équateur Province had a total area of 403,292 km<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> (equivalent to the land area of France) and contained 28% of the total forest area in the DRC (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib49" id="crosref0260">United Nations Development Program, 2009</ce:cross-ref>). The study site in Bikoro territory, located in the southwest of the province accommodating swamp equatorial rainforest, inundated year-round, making road construction and maintenance difficult (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib55" id="crosref0265">Yamba, 2009</ce:cross-ref>). The site in the Gemena territory is in the northwest of the province, now the Sud-Ubangi province, and is characterized by lowland dense humid rainforest that transitions into evergreen savannah woodland and grasses.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">The population of both areas rely heavily on forests for their livelihoods for consumption and sale of goods, by practicing slash and burn, shifting cultivation, extraction of non-timber forest products (NTFPs), hunting and charcoal production. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0270">Samndong et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> report that timber and NTFPs are the second most important source of income, behind farming, accounting for approximately 24.2% and 18.8% of total household income in Bikoro and Gemena respectively. The land and forests in both areas is <ce:italic>de jure</ce:italic> owned and managed by the state, as defined by the 1973 Land Ordinance and the 2002 Forest Code. Socially embedded customary institutions define the de-facto property rights, to which the local population is strongly attached. Land is considered as a common heritage, both as physical and cultural inheritance from ancestors (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0275">Samndong et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The market price survey questionnaire relied on people's own perceptions and reported values about household wealth and net income in their local context. Data were collected from May to August 2013 and July to August 2014. Price information was collected and analysed in Congolese Francs but is presented here in United States Dollar equivalents for ease of reference based on an exchange rate of 1800 Congolese Francs to the US Dollar. Local impressions of wealth are site-specific, making inter-community comparisons of households difficult (e.g., a wealthy household in one community might be poor in another). A monetary estimate of total household income (adjusted per adult equivalent unit) was made so that households can be allocated to income quantiles as a basis for comparison. An assessment was made of the demographic composition of each household. Data were collected on total household income in terms of sale and consumption of own agricultural produce and harvested environmental goods such as fuel wood and bushmeat.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">In the CV section of the questionnaire, respondents were asked to state their minimum level of compensation required to forgo access to timber and NTFPs from their local protected area for a period of one year. The questionnaire used an open-ended CV format, in which respondents state their minimum willingness-to-accept (WTA) compensation. The scenario sets up a framework for the implementation of a hypothetical, novel community-based resource management scheme, in collaboration with local management authorities. It stipulates direct payments for forest conservation as compensation for loss of access to local forests, as an incentive for protection. The bidding is open-ended, based on the respondents perceived required level of compensation to lose direct benefits from the protected area on an annual basis and employed a provision point mechanism,<ce:cross-ref refid="fn1" id="crosref0280">
                           <ce:sup loc="post">1</ce:sup>
                        </ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:footnote id="fn1">
                           <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                           <ce:note-para id="ntpara0010" view="all">A provision point mechanism is a statement delivered as part of the CV narrative that a good of a predetermined magnitude and institutional form is provided only if the sum of contributions from a defined group equals or exceeds its cost. The provision point was presented in the narrative as, “The community is being asked to make monetary bids to assess the demand for such a scheme and estimate the level of compensation. Only limited amounts of funds are available for the scheme. If the sum of all the communities' compensation amounts is less than or equal to the money available, then the scheme would go ahead as described.”</ce:note-para>
                        </ce:footnote> proven to reduce hypothetical over-statement of WTA compensation amounts (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib5" id="crosref0285">Bush et al., 2013</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib39" id="crosref0290">Poe et al., 2002</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib42" id="crosref0295">Rondeau et al., 1999</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="bib41" id="crosref0300">2005</ce:cross-ref>). The WTA approach is policy relevant in the DRC, in that the REDD + strategy is orientated around the principle of “payments for performance” and benefits sharing mechanisms at the local level to create incentives for voluntary compliance with forest conservation objectives. Here we use the term “compensation” to mean providing direct payments to offset the foregone benefits of forest access.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">A group of trained enumerators administered and pre-tested the survey in the field. Surveying was rigorously supervised to ensure compliance with established procedures. Weaknesses in the presentation and comprehension of the tool by both the enumerators and respondents were identified during pre-testing and resolved by further training and adjustments to the survey tool. In general, there was consensus from enumerators that the scenario was believable for respondents. Importantly, the scenario addressed both a real conservation issue (illegal use) and an appropriate response to resolving it (direct payment for conservation) with an enforceable set of rules, as such it was plausible and policy relevant. Further, conservation education and awareness programs that have been operational around the protected area sites in recent years may have significantly aided local comprehension of issues raised in the survey. Execution of the CV exercise alongside the market price survey may also have helped to produce a more considered response to the CV question and avoided confusion in responses. A more detailed description of the data collection effort and a map of survey sites is available in <ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0305">Samndong et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref>. Given the complexity of collecting household survey data with multiple response sets, analyses presented have different numbers of observations due to households’ omitted responses to some variables.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec2.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0045">Model specification</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">The regression analysis can be executed with many different model specifications, depending on the CV elicitation format. Our open-ended CVM survey allows the WTA compensation to be considered as a ‘continuous’ dependent variable. Therefore, the following semi-log model is specified:<ce:display>
                           <ce:formula id="ufd1">
                              <mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">Log</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">(</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi>W</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi>T</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mo stretchy="true">)</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mn>0</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                    <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">+</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi>ε</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:msub>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:math>
                           </ce:formula>
                        </ce:display>where <mml:math altimg="si2.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msub>
                                 <mml:mi>β</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mn>0</mml:mn>
                              </mml:msub>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is a constant term, <mml:math altimg="si3.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">β</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si4.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">X</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> represent vectors of coefficients and explanatory variables, and <mml:math altimg="si5.svg">
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi>ε</mml:mi>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:math> is an IID error term. The explanatory variables are identified based on basic economic theory and literature reviews. Thus, our explanatory variables are comprised of socioeconomic characteristics of the respondent and other factors such as experience in forest resource use, a position in village committee, conflict over farmland access, and perception on climate change. Regression models were estimated in STATA, and the description and measurements of all variables included in the regression analysis are provided in <ce:cross-ref refid="appsec1" id="crosref0310">Appendix 1</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec3" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0050">Results and discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.1" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0055">Descriptive statistics</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">As shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1" id="crosref0315">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl1"/>, male respondents are overrepresented in the samples from both sites. This over-representation is unsurprising, as the survey method selected household heads who are typically male. About 61% of respondents in Bikoro and about 40% in Gemena have completed secondary education. Respondents with no formal education make up less than 20% of the sample in both sites. In respect to ethnicity, Mongos dominate the sample, making up 52% of respondents in Bikoro and 83% in Gemena. About 41% of the respondents are locally migrated. Regarding the dimensions of social status, several respondents indicated that they held positions in at least one local or regional association. For instance, about 33% of respondents hold some sort of position in a religious group and about 17% in a village committee.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">There are statistically significant differences between the two sites in terms of family size, farmland size, the quantity of crops produced and sold, the amount of income from farming, from charcoal, and from fishing, as well as in total household income (see <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl2" id="crosref0320">Table 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl2"/>). The average age of respondents is approximately 44 years and the maximum age 85 years. Family size ranges from 1 to 36 persons per household. Farmland size is also different between the two sites and range from 0.2 to 13 ha. Farming is clearly the largest contributor to household income for both sites (accounting for 76% and 81% of total income for Bikoro and Gemena respectively). Respondents at both sites also report lesser amounts of income earned from forest products, such as charcoal and NTFPs, and other economic activities including fishing. It is noticeable that forest dwellers are usually dependent on forest resources for their substance livelihoods. However, the income from the forest, which includes only the financial income obtained from the sale of charcoal and NTFPs (and which doesn't consist of household consumption), only represents a minor portion of the goods and services obtained from forests.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">It is important to note that the proportion of income obtained from forests varies significantly between individuals, when classified by income quintiles. As presented in <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl3" id="crosref0325">Table 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl3"/>, forest income contributes to 52% of household income for the lowest income quintile, whereas the share of forest income for the highest income quintile is only 15% and for the third (middle) income quintile, 25%.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">The mean amount of compensation required to forgo use of the forest is much larger than reported annual average income for both Bikoro and Gemena. Respondents in Bikoro would require an annual compensation of approximately 1139 USD, while those in Gemena would ask for 1143 USD. On average across both sites, 75% of respondents required a compensation higher than their reported income level. It may be that respondents overestimate their forgone benefits and ask for higher compensation. Alternatively, it may be that the benefits of the forest cannot be expressed solely in terms of financial income. As illustrated in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0330">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"/>, for most respondents, the amount of compensation is approximately $1000 per annum per household, whereas annual reported household income is less than $500. In general, the stated amount of compensation required is approximately twice annual household income.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">We further examine the divergence in household value measures by creating a variable that is the ratio of contingent valuation to financial price estimate. An even more pronounced difference was observed between reported forest income and WTA compensation. As illustrated in <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl4" id="crosref0335">Table 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl4"/>, the ratio of WTA to forest income is approximately 13:1. Again, this differs by income quintile. The lowest income quintile requires a compensation to forest income ratio of approximately 50:1, the highest income quintile a ratio of approximately 7:1, the third (middle) quintile a ratio of approximately 17:1. This provides a clear indication of the significance of forests to the poorest households and, consequently, the importance of considering equity aspects in conservation programs.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">Further, there is noticeable variation in the compensation required by different social groups. For instance, those with a position in an association or group required a higher amount than those without such a position. The compensation required by Mongo is higher than any other ethnic group, and from the Bikoro region, where a higher proportion of household income comes from forest goods, reflecting a lack of alternative livelihoods options relative to other groups. As shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0340">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"/>, the amount of compensation for the Mongo and Ntomba ethnic groups is higher than for other ethnic groups. Similarly, females ask for a higher level of compensation than males. Further, females from the Ekonda, Ntomba, and Batwa ethnic groups request a higher level of compensation than female respondents from other ethnic groups. Note that the greater variation in required compensation for female respondents may be an artifice of the small sample size (n = 31).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.2" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0060">Estimation results</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">The amount of compensation is not found to be normally distributed when evaluated using the Shapiro-Wilk test of normality (Z statistic = 8.93) (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib43" id="crosref0345">Royston, 1992</ce:cross-ref>). Therefore, we applied a logarithmic transformation of WTA compensation and a semi-log linear regression. As indicated in <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl5" id="crosref0350">Table 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="tbl5"/>, the regression on the pooled data has an R-squared value of 16%. A better model performance is indicated for the sub samples with R-squared values of 27% for site 1 and 29% for site 2.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">The socio-demographic variables gender, age, and education are insignificant in cases of the pooled data set. On the contrary, family size, the social status indicators <ce:italic>ethnicity</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>position in village committee</ce:italic>, forest income, annual sale of crops, and expectation of increasing forest use are all highly significant. The positive coefficient for family size indicates higher compensation payments for larger family households i.e., having one more individual in a household increases WTA compensation by about 2%. The negative coefficient for <ce:italic>ethnicity</ce:italic> implies higher compensations for the Mongo ethnic group. In other words, all other ethnic groups are willing to accept a compensation amount of about 46% less than the compensation to be paid for the Mongos. Likewise, having a <ce:italic>position in a village committee</ce:italic> is significant with a positive coefficient i.e., those at position would like to get a compensation amount of 41% higher than ordinary households. The forest income is also significant and positively influence households WTA, but the effect is only marginal. In contrast, those who could sell more than half of the crops produced would ask for a 28% less compensation payment in contrast to those who could sell less than half of their crop production. Households’ expectation of increases in future forest resource uses has small but positive effect on their WTA compensation payments i.e., those households would ask for a 29% higher payment. Households who experience conflict over land access for farming require 21% higher compensation than those who do not (but significant only at 10%). Moreover, we can observe the differences between the two pilot sites i.e. respondents living in Bikoro require about 22% (but only at 10% significance levels) higher compensation that those living in Gemena.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">The subsamples yield quite different results. In Bikoro (n = 153), male respondents are willing to accept a compensation of approximately 53% less than female respondents, <ce:italic>ceteris paribus</ce:italic>. The <ce:italic>age</ce:italic> of the respondent is significant, positively influencing the respondent's WTA; the required compensation increases by 1% for a one-year older person. Respondents having a <ce:italic>position in a village committee</ce:italic> would require 70% higher compensation than those who are not. In addition, those experiencing an economic shock would ask for a 35% higher annual compensation. Turning to the sample from Gemena (n = 172), <ce:italic>ethnicity</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>position in village committee, annual sale of crops</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>conflict over farmland access</ce:italic> are highly significant variables. The coefficient for ethnicity is positive implying about 99% higher compensation for the Mongo ethnic group. Note that our subsample for this site is overrepresented by the Mongos. Respondents with a <ce:italic>position in a village committee</ce:italic> require 34% higher compensation. On the contrary, those whose <ce:italic>annual sale of crops produced</ce:italic> accounts for more than half of total production would ask for a 30% less compensation. Respondents experiencing conflict in farmland access would be willing to accept a 36% higher compensation. Age of the respondent and experiencing economic shock are significant (at 10% level) and negatively related to the WTA compensation.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec3.3" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sectitle0065">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">While existing drivers of deforestation in the two sites are more-or-less similar, local livelihood strategies and available resources could justify observed differences in the determinants (and levels) of the amount of compensation required for forest conservation. For instance, while agricultural expansion and wood extraction were mentioned as the main drivers of deforestation in both sites (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0355">Samndong et al., 2018</ce:cross-ref>); there is a slight difference in the extent of deforestation. In Bikoro, a larger proportion of the landscape is swamp forest that hinders timber extraction but promotes more permanent farming, which would result in higher opportunity cost of forest conservation. In contrast, the forest in Gemena is characterized by dense humid rainforest where local communities are mainly engaged in slash and burn farming as well as hunting activities with lower opportunity cost of forest conservation. Therefore, such a difference in forest use experience could be one possible explanation for the differences in determinants of compensation shown in the estimation results. This is supported by the finding that in Gemena, those who sold more than half of their crops required less compensation to forgo forest access than those who do not, pointing to the benefits of being integrated into agricultural markets and thus less reliant on forest resources.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">The differences in local contexts could also be linked to socio-economic factors. For instance, female respondents in the Bikoro site require higher compensation, perhaps because they are not getting enough resources from the dense swamp forest. In other words, it can be argued that men who are responsible for obtaining forest products from the dense forest, and who are aware of the difficulties, are likely to accept access restrictions at lower compensation than women. This result could also be explained by the nature of goods harvested by men and women. Men tend to harvest high-value products infrequently for cash income (e.g., bushmeat) whereas women tend to harvest lower value products frequently for subsistence (e.g., fuel wood). In general, households with more female members (labor), farm assets, and high social capital are more responsible for large forest clearance for farming. The impact of social status, measured in this instance by holding a position in a village committee, can be linked to the perception of dignifying the position. In least developing countries, such positions are essential for better living conditions and are associated with a tendency to take larger shares of benefits in any circumstances (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib15" id="crosref0360">du Preez and Sturman, 2009</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib50" id="crosref0365">Vargas et al., 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1" id="crosref0370">Almeida-Leñero et al., 2017</ce:cross-ref>). As outlined in <ce:cross-ref refid="bib44" id="crosref0375">Samndong et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref>, the benefits from timber extraction goes to those in higher political or economic positions. This could explain the link between socio-economic and institutional status and level of dependency on the forest resource, and hence the amount of compensation required to forego forest access. Therefore, conservation mechanisms in developing countries would require evaluating the optimal level of compensation for forgone benefits as well as the distributional impacts of the programs for effective conservation outcomes. Moreover, from a demand side perspective, the buyers of ecosystem services in PES designs are often concerned about fair distribution of payments (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib40" id="crosref0380">Randrianarison and Waetzold, 2017</ce:cross-ref>) or social outcomes (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0385">de Lima et al., 2019</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">We see some interesting paradoxical recommendations derived from the findings, when for example from an efficiency perspective, it seems we should work with higher income households and from an equity perspective, we should target poorer households. Mixing development and conservation objectives in one economic policy tool may not result in the maximum outcome in one or another of the objectives; there will always be a compromise. The most basic rule of economic policy is that there must be at least as many instruments specifically designed to meet an objective as there are objectives (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib8" id="crosref0390">Colman and Young, 1989</ce:cross-ref>). From the outset, it is necessary for project planners to be clear about their specific priorities – whether it is forest conservation or rural development; REDD+ and many other PES schemes are primarily forest (and by association, biodiversity) conservation mechanisms. The issue then is looking for an optimal solution, maximizing forest conservation benefits whilst minimizing the social and economic costs. Partly the paradox also arises from how the terms effectiveness, efficiency and equity are defined, which must be done based on the priority objective of the project. For PES schemes to be implemented successfully successful, project proponents need a clear indication of the marginal value of what a community gives-up (their opportunity cost) in exchange for forgone practices or forest uses (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib4" id="crosref0395">Buckwell et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Arguably, the best people to judge the acceptability of community-based schemes are communities themselves. As noted in Chapter 7 of the <ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0400">Dasgupta Review (2021)</ce:cross-ref>, the tropics are rich in biodiversity and many of the world's poorest countries are in the tropics, PES schemes are, therefore, typically built around poor communities. Local inhabitants are key players, without their engagement, these ecosystems will not be protected. In order to effectively align values in the context of the DRC successful PES will also require generating the public and private investments to achieve good community governance and transparency (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib37" id="crosref0405">Morgan et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>) and in capacity building (<ce:cross-ref refid="bib36" id="crosref0410">Morgan et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>) to ensure effective economic coordination.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">The findings in this study have important implications for the choice of forest management approach when comparing direct versus indirect methods of creating incentives. Research by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0415">Groom and Palmer (2008)</ce:cross-ref> on the cost-effectiveness of direct payment approaches, such as PES, contests the findings of <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0420">Ferraro and Simpson (2002)</ce:cross-ref> that they are in fact a superior alternative to indirect approaches such as Integrated Conservation and Development schemes. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib26" id="crosref0425">Groom and Palmer (2008)</ce:cross-ref> argue that <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0430">Ferraro and Simpson's (2002)</ce:cross-ref> conditions of perfect elasticity in supply or demand, enabling agents to purchase profit maximizing quantities of inputs at prevailing market prices, is unrealistic in most developing country contexts. They propose instead that inputs and outputs may be subject to quantity constraints or rationing, concluding that direct payments are not necessarily more cost-effective than indirect payments, and that there are instances where the parties involved prefer indirect payment mechanisms e.g., development project approaches. Thus, we see that in the choice of the most cost-effective approach, an understanding of the local institutional context is essential in providing the maximum welfare (economic) benefits. This seems like a realistic proposition in the context of forest reliant households, operating in imperfect markets with low substitutability of money for alternatives to forest products. In such settings, direct payments in practice may not in fact result in the optimal conservation and welfare outcome. These findings highlight the need to account for the financial and economic values of forest access <ce:italic>a priori</ce:italic> if PES avoided deforestation initiatives are to reach their potential.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec4" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0070">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">Building upon <ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0435">Dasgupta's (2021)</ce:cross-ref> observation that, despite mixed progress to date, PES schemes hold great potential to conserve biodiversity in low-income countries, with their success depending on program design and scale of funding, the purpose of this paper was to examine the financial and economic costs of achieving primary forest conservation, while generating insights into PES design in the context of remote rural communities in central DRC.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">Bearing in mind the previously defined two key challenges for policy makers, 1) what level of benefit will result in a desired behavioral change (opportunity cost estimation), and 2) equitable sharing of benefits, how social and economic factors affect welfare values, we examined the divergence in value measures between market price (financial) and CV (economic) methods. As an indicator of financial cost, the market price method derived a relatively low contribution of forest access to household income; mean annual forest income was $93.60, representing just 23% of mean total household income across the sample. Further, 24% of households reported no forest income at all. The financial value of local forest resources was much higher for high-income households than low-income households, but the inverse was true of forest income as a proportion of total income. It is often suggested that poverty is a driving factor behind forest use and thus improving incomes will reduce forest use. These findings suggest the opposite; <ce:italic>ceteris paribus</ce:italic>, improving income may increase the general off take of forest goods, echoing findings by <ce:cross-ref refid="bib30" id="crosref0440">Jagger (2008)</ce:cross-ref>. We do not imply that poverty is not a problem, as most of the households in the survey are poor or ultra-poor by world standards, simply that the assumed relationship between income (as a measure of poverty) and forest use does not hold in the context of this study. It is logical to assume that the struggle to avoid further reduction into poverty, or, for a few, to leverage whatever natural forest resources may be available to climb out of poverty, that drives forest use.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">In welfare terms, as measured by minimum WTA compensation, the opportunity cost of forest conservation was almost as much as 50% of total annual household income and nearly 13 times more than the financial cost value of forest goods. This difference, whilst large, is not surprising, as the methods essentially measure different things. The welfare value reflects the substantial non-market use of forest resources and the potential local economic losses imposed by forest management policies. This value can also reflect the level of market imperfection, in that the substitutability of goods for money in a peasant farming economy, in the face of sudden scarcity, is low. Alternative resources are often not available, even if households have money to buy them. Economic cost estimates also include the value of access to forest resources as insurance in times of local scarcity. An important finding was that social (non-market) values associated with forest income can be higher for low-income households than for high-income households. This may reflect the relative importance between economic classes of household on forest resources e.g., dependence for low-income households (few alternatives to forest income) versus use as a livelihood alternative for high-income households.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">Reframing the policy question from the perspective of the emerging markets for avoided deforestation credits could be formulated on the supply side as “how much is my forest carbon worth?” or on the demand side “how much should I pay for a given carbon credit? Thus we have a critical dilemma, what price represents fair value for compensation? In the context of this study, financial values are much lower than social values. However, community benefits priced at the finical level are unlikely to provide sufficient incentive to scale and sustain participation from communities in avoided deforestation programs, particularly when markets do not function well and the utility of cash to convert to goods and services is limited. On the other hand, the welfare estimate does not directly equate to the financial price that would provide a fair incentive as it accounts for non-market contextual factors in how forest contribute to overall welfare including cultural and livelihoods risk management.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">In terms of the scale of funding question, with almost 56% of the DRC population (approximately 9,950,800 households) living in rural forest landscapes, a crude estimated cost of annual compensation to conserve the entire primary forest estate in financial terms is just under 1 billion USD ($931, 394, 880) compared to a welfare estimate of just over 12 billion USD ($12, 108, 133,440).<ce:cross-ref refid="fn2" id="crosref0445">
                        <ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>
                     </ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:footnote id="fn2">
                        <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                        <ce:note-para id="ntpara0015" view="all">Authors' estimate using results from the survey and World Bank population data for the DRC <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/dr-congo-population" id="intref0020" xlink:type="simple">https://worldpopulationreview.com/countries/dr-congo-population</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:note-para>
                     </ce:footnote> Critically, this underlines the need to better estimate the local social impacts of forest conservation practices, where accurate estimation can dramatically alter perspectives on the marginal abatement costs of primary forest conservation, and lead to improved design and costing of policy. There has to be prioritization about how much forest will be possible to conserve with available budgets and what strategies need to be deployed to maximize the equitable sharing of benefits. Adopting survey methods as described in this case study can be invaluable in designing more effective policy in complex socio-economic and weak market settings.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">Forest conservation strategies aimed at subsistence farming households, using direct or indirect compensation methods, must do more than compensate the financial values lost to ensure local equity. Simply improving incomes, a central tenet of poverty alleviation programs, may not help to conserve forests, especially without effective enforcement of regulations, a critical issue related to effectiveness. In addition, working with households closest to the target forest will be more effective than working with households further away. In terms of efficiency, defined here as how much forest conservation money can buy, targeting households that are highly dependent on the forest, with subsistence farming activities (i.e., engaging in slash and burn practices), and those in some sort of leadership position, will yield a larger impact per unit of investment than working with wealthier, disconnected households or those further away from the forest sites. Gender inclusiveness (i.e. local women's engagement and access for fair compensation payments) is another central issue to be considered in PES design. Results also suggest that facilitating household access to agricultural markets, reduces the compensation required to foregoing forest access and use.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">The described results are critical factors when thinking about efforts to pursue community-based approaches to forest management. Any alternative activities to forest use must be designed to offset the local welfare (economic) loss rather than simply the financial loss to maintain household participation. In addition, the social perspective on the value of forest resources is not static and may change over time. A quantitative understanding of the scope and nature of costs and benefits helps realistic planning in terms of understanding the investments required to implement successful programs. The choice of valuation approach can dramatically affect our estimates of the scale of compensation required to affect real change in forest conservation. Ideally, we should attempt to use both financial and economic approaches, as they are different but complementary measures of opportunity cost. The financial values track quantity changes and market variables, giving important insights into the changing nature of the demand for and supply of forest products. The economic (welfare) value gives a quantitative measure of the social impacts of policy and management approaches, helping us to understand equity and dependency issues.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec5" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0075">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Glenn Bush:</ce:bold> Conceptualization, Data curation, Investigation, Methodology, Project administration, Supervision, Writing – original draft, Writing – review &amp; editing. <ce:bold>Fitalew Agimass Taye:</ce:bold> Conceptualization, Data curation, Formal analysis, Methodology, Writing – original draft. <ce:bold>Christopher Fleming:</ce:bold> Conceptualization, Data curation, Investigation, Resources, Writing – original draft. <ce:bold>Raymond Achu Samndong:</ce:bold> Data curation, Investigation, Project administration, Writing – original draft.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0010" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0080">Declaration of competing interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0010" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sectitle0085">Acknowledgements</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">The analysis reported here were supported in part by a private charitable trust that wishes to remain anonymous to avoid unsolicited funding requests. The trust has had no influence on the design, analysis, interpretation and documentation of this research. The data were originally collected as part of the PhD research for Raymond Samndong supported by the <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs15" sponsor-id="https://doi.org/10.13039/501100005416" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">Norwegian Research Council</ce:grant-sponsor> through the Man and Forest Research Project <ce:grant-number refid="gs15">2014–2016</ce:grant-number>, led by Prof. Arild Vatn. Projet Equateur, a program of the Woodwell Climate Research Center (previously the Woods Hole Research Center), facilitated the data collection in the DRC. The authors would like to thank the community members who generously gave their time to participate in the survey and numerous local stakeholders motivated to conserve their primary forests and natural heritage that helped to make this research project happen.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
               <ce:section id="appsec1" view="all">
                  <ce:label>Appendix 1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0090">Description and measurement of explanatory variables</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">
                     <ce:display>
                        <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" frame="topbot" colsep="0" rowsep="0" id="undtbl1">
